            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">
                <placeName>Cincin</placeName>
                <date>February 14 5613</date>
            </p>
            <p>To the <addressee>Revd. I Leeser</addressee>. Sir/</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I beg leave to inform you that the vestry room under our new<lb/>
                Synagogue at the corner of <placeName>6th St. &amp; Broadway</placeName> was
                    <sic>opend</sic> for the 1st time for divine worship<lb/> on <add>Hebrew</add>,
                On which <sic>ocasion</sic> the <persName>Revd. Mr. M Cohen</persName> late
                    <add>Hebrew</add> of the Polish <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> cutter <add>?</add>
                <placeName>London</placeName>, was requested to read the prayers which he did, and
                on the following<lb/> morng. he delivered a lecture in the English language, and on
                    <date>Saturday</date> last, he did the<lb/> same in the german. This gentlemn.
                is here for some time, he is <sic>desireous</sic> to<lb/> obtain a situation, as
                    <add>Hebrew</add> Teacher and lecturer, in this <sic>Contry</sic>, he requests
                me<lb/> to mention this to you, and to support his pretensions with the intent
                that<lb/> you will be good enough to place him through your Occidt. as a
                candidate<lb/> before the public in the above capacity. <persName>Mr.
                    Cohen</persName> is an entire stranger with<lb/> us, he states that he is in
                    <sic>posession</sic> of valuable testimonials from eminent<lb/> persons in
                    <placeName>Europe</placeName>, including one from the <persName>Rd. Dr. N
                    Adler</persName>
                <sic>recomending</sic> him<lb/> &amp; so forth. Our friends here were well pleased
                with his reading of the Prayers<lb/> &amp; the <add>Hebrew</add> which was
                exceedingly correct his lectures were arranged with<lb/> accuracy, and if his
                “Teachings are not founded on the fundamental” Bulwarks of<lb/> our faith, I am
                assured by those, who are capable to pronounce an opinion, that they<lb/>
                <del>are</del> were highly instructive, and very interesting and well supported with
                the reasonings and<lb/> opinions of the best of our commentators. <persName>Mr.
                    C.</persName> does not pretend to be eloquent.<lb/> It cannot be expected that
                every man can be a “<persName>Raphael</persName> or a “<persName>Jacobs</persName>,
                yet this much<lb/> may be said in his favor. That any congregation
                    <sic>requireing</sic> a good teacher for their children<lb/> on agreeable
                    <add>Hebrew</add> who understands what he says for their <add>Hebrew</add> an
                experienced scholar<lb/>
                <sic>posessing</sic> requisite attainments, for expounding our sacred law, &amp;
                &amp;, this gent. will be<lb/> a great acquisition. If the above request is
                compatible with the regulations of<lb/> the Occidet. be pleased to notice it. I may
                mention that the article<lb/> headed Le Justus Milieu in the last <hi
                    rend="underline">number</hi> was well recd by many in
                    <placeName>Cin.</placeName> while to others it was not <sic>to</sic><lb/>
                acceptable. The <persName>Revd I. Rosenfelt</persName> in particular has declared
                war to the knifer<add>?</add> against<lb/>
                <persName>Mr. Matyer</persName> &amp; <persName>D. Myers</persName>. Facts are
                stubborn things, and not very palatable to those who<lb/> are regardless of the
                truth. I am afraid that my letter which accompanied<lb/> the one of <persName>Messr.
                    Matyer</persName> &amp; <persName>Myers</persName> will <hi rend="underline">be
                    out of place</hi> in the next Occidt. unless<lb/> corrected by yourself, should
                this be likewise your opinion, I will not feel in<lb/> any way
                    <sic>disapointed</sic> by its omission. Our object is so far attained,<lb/> I
                desire good will and peace with all men. I remain yours very Respy.=<persName
                    role="author">Saml. Bruel</persName></p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>To the <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Editor of the Occident</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <placeName>Phila</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(3)"><placeName>Pa</placeName>_</p>
